05279nam a22007935i 9780812297300DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122973007 a10.9783/97808122973002doi  a(DE-B1597)563166  a(OCoLC)1183962461  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aDS156.P8bM337 2020 7aHIS0020202bisacsh04a939/.332231 aMadsen, Jesper Majbom, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFrom Trophy Towns to City-States :bUrban Civilization and Cultural Identities in Roman Pontus /cJesper Majbom Madsen. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b9 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEmpire and After00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. The Eternal Hunt for Glory -- tChapter 2. Building Cities from the Ground -- tChapter 3. Introducing Civic Life -- tChapter 4. Eager to Be Both Greek and Roman -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 66 BCE, in the woods of Armenia Minor, Pompey the Great defeated Mithridates VI Eupator, making him one of the most successful Roman generals of all time. The victory presented him with the enormous challenge of organizing not only Mithridates' kingdom but also large parts of Anatolia and the Near East that were now placed under Roman rule. Pompey's solution was to found six new cities and to convert two existing communities, Zela, a temple community dedicated to the goddess Anaïtis, and Amaseia, the former royal residence, into cities as well. There would now be eight city-states, each with the responsibility of administering the territory known to the Romans as Pontus.It has often been argued that in their eastern provinces the Romans based newly founded cities on the model of the Greek city-state and that Roman culture had less influence there than in the West. Jesper Majbom Madsen, however, describes civic development in Roman Pontus as a process by which Roman and Greek elements were introduced simultaneously. He contends that the Pompeian cities were neither traditional Greek poleis nor entirely Roman settlements with Roman laws and legislation; nor were they Greek cities gradually influenced by Roman rule. Instead, they represented a third category, in which a citizen could be an Anatolian, Greek, and Roman at the same time as well as a member of the elite, a priest in the imperial cult and in a cult to Asclepius, a local politician and a member of the Pontic koinon, all without contradiction.Bringing together a wide range of literary, historical, and political sources, From Trophy Towns to City-States examines how Pompey's cities were initially organized, how they developed over time, and how inhabitants in this part of the Roman Empire defined themselves culturally and politically.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aCities and towns, AncientzTurkey. 0aCity-stateszTurkeyxHistory. 0aRomanszTurkeyxHistory. 0aUrbanizationzRome. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / Rome.2bisacsh  aAncient Studies.  aArchaeology.  aClassics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2020 Englishz978311070483908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2020z9783110704631oZDB-23-DGD08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUPP Frontlist eBook-Package 2020z978311069044640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/97808